    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Yes, that's correct. The escrow agent primarily acts as a middleman to ensure that the transaction proceeds smoothly and that both parties fulfill their obligations. Regarding property taxes and insurance, these are typically handled separately from the escrow account used for the real estate transaction itself.\n\nProperty taxes are usually paid directly to the local government or tax authority, and the buyer and seller would need to arrange for these payments as part of the closing process. The escrow agent may assist in coordinating the transfer of property tax responsibilities from the seller to the buyer, but they do not directly handle these payments.\n\nInsurance, on the other hand, is often arranged through an insurance company or agent. The buyer would need to obtain homeowners insurance for the property, and this would be a separate process from the real estate transaction. The escrow agent may help facilitate the transfer of the property title and ensure that all necessary documents are in order, but they would not typically be involved in arranging or managing insurance policies.\n\nIn summary, while the escrow agent plays a crucial role in ensuring a smooth and secure real estate transaction, property taxes and insurance are handled separately and would require coordination with the appropriate tax authorities and insurance providers.",
